  <div class="resource-body">

    <p>If your pediatrician has suggested an autism assessment — or if you've been wondering whether your child should have one — it helps to know exactly what you're walking into.</p>

    <h2>What is an autism assessment?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      An autism assessment is a structured evaluation conducted by a trained professional to determine whether a child meets the diagnostic criteria for Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD). It looks at how a child communicates, socializes, behaves, and processes the world around them.
    </div>
    <p>It's not a single test. An autism assessment is a process — it typically involves observation, standardized testing, parent interviews, and a review of developmental history. The goal isn't just to arrive at a yes or no answer. It's to build a picture of how your child's brain works, where their strengths are, and where they need support.</p>

    <h2>Who conducts an autism assessment?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      Autism assessments are conducted by licensed professionals including developmental pediatricians, child psychologists, neuropsychologists, and in some cases speech-language pathologists and occupational therapists working as part of a multidisciplinary team.
    </div>
    <p>The specific professional depends on your location, your child's age, and what concerns prompted the referral. In many areas, a full diagnostic assessment is done by a team rather than a single clinician — this is considered best practice because autism affects multiple developmental domains.</p>

    <h2>What does an autism assessment look at?</h2>
    <p>Assessors look at four core areas:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Social communication</strong> — how your child initiates and responds to social interaction, eye contact, facial expressions, and back-and-forth conversation</li>
      <li><strong>Restricted and repetitive behaviors</strong> — patterns of behavior, routines, sensory sensitivities, and intense interests</li>
      <li><strong>Developmental history</strong> — when your child reached milestones like first words, first steps, and how their development has unfolded over time</li>
      <li><strong>Cognitive and adaptive functioning</strong> — problem-solving, daily living skills, and how your child manages tasks independently</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Is an autism assessment the same as a diagnosis?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      No. An autism assessment is the process; a diagnosis is the outcome. After completing the assessment, the clinician reviews all the information and determines whether your child meets the DSM-5 criteria for Autism Spectrum Disorder.
    </div>
    <p>Not every assessment leads to a diagnosis. Some children have characteristics consistent with autism but don't meet the full criteria. Others may receive a related diagnosis such as ADHD, developmental language disorder, or sensory processing differences. All of these findings are valuable — the goal is clarity, not a label.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-label">From Dr. Kyle Daigle</span>
      "The assessment isn't about finding something wrong with your child. It's about understanding how they experience the world — so you can meet them where they are and give them the support they actually need."
    </div>

    <h2>What's the difference between a screening and a full assessment?</h2>
    <p>A <strong>screening</strong> is a brief tool — often a questionnaire or a short observation — used to identify whether a child may be at risk and should be referred for further evaluation. Your child's pediatrician may use a tool like the M-CHAT (Modified Checklist for Autism in Toddlers) at well-child visits.</p>
    <p>A <strong>full assessment</strong> is a comprehensive evaluation that takes several hours and uses validated diagnostic tools such as the ADOS-2 (Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule) and ADI-R (Autism Diagnostic Interview-Revised). A screening can flag concerns; only a full assessment can provide a diagnosis.</p>

    <h2>Do you need a referral for an autism assessment?</h2>
    <p>In most cases, yes — your child's pediatrician or family doctor will provide a referral to a specialist or evaluation clinic. Some private practices accept self-referrals. Insurance coverage typically requires a referral. In school settings, parents can also request an educational evaluation at no cost, though school evaluations assess educational need rather than providing a clinical diagnosis.</p>

